The certification exam itself.

The docker certified associate is administered by mirantis, who acquired docker's enterprise business, and it tests practical docker knowledge across six domains. The format is around fifty-five multiple-choice and multiple-select questions in ninety minutes, taken online and proctored from home or an office. The passing score sits somewhere around two-thirds, though the exact number is not published, and the certification is valid for two years.

The six domains carry different weights, so it helps to know where the marks are. Orchestration is the largest slice, around a quarter, covering swarm, services, stacks, rolling updates, scaling, placement, and secrets. Image creation, management, and registry is close behind, around a fifth, covering the dockerfile, multi-stage builds, tagging, registries, and image security. Installation and configuration, and networking, and security each take roughly a sixth, covering installing and configuring the engine, the full set of network drivers and publishing, and the hardening topics from notebook eight. And storage and volumes rounds it out at around a tenth.

The encouraging part is that every one of those domain pillars maps directly onto this curriculum. Images are notebook two, runtime is notebook three, storage is notebook four, networking is notebook five, security is notebook eight, orchestration is notebook nine, and installation and configuration is this notebook. So preparing for the exam is really just consolidating what you have already worked through, with an eye to which domains carry the most weight.
